targets=Technology.RemindGettingPopupsOnDifferentPlatforms,Technology.Remind,Technology.IncludeMe,Category.Articles,Category.HowTos
text=!! Getting pop-up notifications on various platforms%0a%0aAt the suggestion of the remind author, I set up remind to use something that can be defined separately for each platform, but called the same in the remind file.%0a%0aDavid's suggestion was to write a script that could be called for each platform:%0a(:source lang=email:)%0aOn Fri, Apr 06, 2012 at 02:08:55PM -0400, David F. Skoll wrote:%0a> On Fri, 6 Apr 2012 12:49:29 -0500%0a> tamouse mailing lists wrote:%0a>%0a>> I'd like to be able to have a conditional that determines which OS%0a>> is running (possibly by querying uname) and set the program in the%0a>> reminder file itself. Any suggestions as to how I might do this?%0a>%0a> Wouldn't it be easier to write a little shell script called%0a> "popup-reminder" or something and have that call the appropriate%0a> program on each system?  The Linux "popup-reminder" would call the Linux%0a> program and the Mac OS one would call the Mac OS program.%0a>%0a> Then in your Reminders file, you just use:%0a>%0a> REM ... RUN /usr/local/bin/popup-reminder ...%0a>%0a> Regards,%0a> David.%0a(:sourceend:)%0a%0aThis solution would probably work, but I was a bit reluctant to put something in a global directory ''(I don't know '''why''' exactly -- I'm the only user on both systems.)'' so instead I used an [[Wikipedia:Environment_variable|envar]] to give the shell command to execute for the popup.%0a%0a!! NOTIFY Enironment Variable%0a%0aNOTIFY is an [[Wikipedia:Environment_variable|environment variable]] that contains a string for a shell command to execute to pop up the reminder.%0a%0aOn Ubuntu, the NOTIFY command that works best is:%0a     NOTIFY='/usr/bin/notify-send -t 0 REMINDER'%0a%0aOn Mac, the NOTIFY command should be:%0a     NOTIFY='/usr/local/bin/growlnotify --sticky --message'%0aFor this to work the entire message must be quoted%0a%0aOn non-Ubuntu linuxen or other unixen with X Windows, you can probably gin something up with xmessage:%0a     NOTIFY='/usr/bin/xmessage -center'%0a%0aBest place to set this is in your @@$HOME/.profile@@.%0a%0a>>important%3c%3c%0aDON'T FORGET TO EXPORT NOTIFY.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aTo use this feature, run remind in server-mode:%0a%0a  remind -z %3cremind-files> &%0a%0a(Include the & to send it to the background.)%0a%0a!! Creating events that use the pop-up%0a%0aThe way the RUN directive works, however, means you effectively have to put the event in twice:%0a# so it shows up in the regular run of remind -q (no events)%0a# so it can be used to run a pop-up notification using the $NOTIFY envar%0a%0aIn your .rem file, create an event as follows:%0a%0a(:code:)%0aREM %3cdatespec> MSG '%3creminder text>'%0aREM %3cdatespec> AT %3ctimespec> RUN $NOTIFY '%3creminder text>'%0a(:codeend:)%0a%0aFor example:%0a(:code:)%0aREM 8 Sep 2012 MSG Doctor Appointment at 2:30pm%0aREM 8 Sep 2012 AT 14:30 +1 RUN $NOTIFY 'Doctor Appointment at 2:20pm'%0a(:codeend:)%0a%0a>>important%3c%3c%0aKeep the reminder text quoted so that it ends up being one shell parameter when the $NOTIFY command is called. This is due to the way growlnotify works on os/x.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a%0a>>comment%3c%3c%0aSummary:Different platforms have different programs to display a pop-up message, Growl on the Mac, D-Sub on Ubuntu, others on other nixen. This describes a technique to make the remind files agnostic, yet giving the capability to the user to handle this%0aParent:(Technology.)Remind%0aIncludeMe:[[(Technology.)Remind]]%0aCategories:[[!Articles]],[[!HowTos]]%0aTags: remind, cross-platform, tools%0a(:tags-hide remind, cross-platform, tools :)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a
